🚨 Why Not OFFSET-Based Pagination?

With will_paginate or any offset-based approach:

LIMIT 10 OFFSET 500000;

If user goes to page 50,000:

Database must scan 500,000 rows

Then discard them

Then return next 10

👉 That becomes slow for large tables

💡 What is Cursor-Based Pagination?

Instead of saying:

Give me page 50

We say:

Give me 10 records after this record

We use a unique, indexed column (usually id or created_at) as a cursor.

🛠 Build Cursor Pagination From Scratch

Let’s assume:

We paginate User

We use id as cursor

We fetch 10 records at a time

🎯 Step 1 — Basic Query

First page:

@users = User.order(:id).limit(10)

This gives first 10 users.

🎯 Step 2 — Next Page Using Cursor

Frontend sends:

/users?cursor=15

Meaning:

Give me records after id 15

Controller:

def index
  if params[:cursor].present?
    @users = User.where("id > ?", params[:cursor])
                 .order(:id)
                 .limit(10)
  else
    @users = User.order(:id).limit(10)
  end
end
🧠 What SQL Looks Like
SELECT * FROM users
WHERE id > 15
ORDER BY id ASC
LIMIT 10;

🔥 No OFFSET.
🔥 No scanning large skipped rows.
🔥 Uses index on id.

This is fast even with millions of records.

🎯 Step 3 — Returning Next Cursor (API Version)

Important for APIs.

def index
  users = if params[:cursor]
            User.where("id > ?", params[:cursor])
                .order(:id)
                .limit(10)
          else
            User.order(:id).limit(10)
          end

  next_cursor = users.last&.id

  render json: {
    users: users,
    next_cursor: next_cursor,
    has_more: users.size == 10
  }
end

Frontend will then call:

/users?cursor=LAST_ID
🔁 Bidirectional Pagination (Previous Page?)

More complex.

To go backward:

User.where("id < ?", params[:cursor])
    .order(id: :desc)
    .limit(10)

Then reverse result in Ruby.

🎯 Using created_at Instead of ID

Better for time-based feeds:

User.where("created_at < ?", params[:cursor])
    .order(created_at: :desc)
    .limit(10)

Used in:

Feeds

Notifications

Activity logs

📊 Offset vs Cursor Comparison

| Feature                  | Offset  | Cursor |
| ------------------------ | ------- | ------ |
| Performance large tables | ❌ Slow  | ✅ Fast |
| Jump to page 50          | ✅ Yes   | ❌ No   |
| Infinite scroll          | 😐 Okay | ✅ Best |
| API friendly             | 😐      | ✅      |


🎤 Interview 1-Minute Answer

You can say:

Offset-based pagination uses LIMIT and OFFSET, which becomes slow for large datasets because the database must scan skipped rows. Cursor-based pagination instead uses a unique indexed column like id or created_at as a reference point and fetches records after that value. This avoids OFFSET scanning and performs efficiently even with millions of records. It’s commonly used in APIs and infinite scroll implementations.

